# Module 9 — Advanced PostgreSQL

This is where PostgreSQL becomes the focus.

Topics to implement naturally:

### CTEs

Build readable academic reports.

---

### Window Functions

Examples:

- Student rank
- **GPA** ranking
- Department toppers

---

### Views

### Student Dashboard

### Teacher Dashboard

### Admin Dashboard

---

### Materialized Views

Semester reports

Attendance summaries

---

### JSONB

Store flexible assignment settings.

Example

```text ### Assignment Settings

submission_deadline

rubric

attachments

late_penalty ```

---

### Full Text Search

Search courses

Search teachers

Search students

---

### Recursive Queries

Department hierarchy

Course prerequisites

---

# Module 10 — Reporting

Build dashboards.

Examples

Student

- **GPA**
- Attendance %
- Completed credits

Teacher

- Assigned courses
- Pending grading

Admin

- Total enrollment
- Revenue
- Student performance
- Department statistics

---

# Module 11 — Testing

Test

Happy path

- Student registers
- Student enrolls
- Attendance recorded
- Exam completed

Failure cases

- Duplicate student
- Invalid course
- Enrollment limit reached
- Missing payment
- Invalid semester

Validate every transaction.

---

# Module 12 — Optimization

Inspect

- Slow queries
- Execution plans
- Missing indexes

Implement

- B-tree indexes
- Composite indexes
- Partial indexes (where appropriate)

Measure improvements with `**EXPLAIN** **ANALYZE**`.

---

# Module 13 — Refactoring

Improve architecture.

Move **SQL** into repositories.

Move business logic into services.

Centralize connection management.

Remove duplicate code.

---

# Final Deliverables

By the end of the project you should have:

- Business Requirement Specification
- User Stories
- Domain Model
- ER Diagram
- Normalized Database Schema
- PostgreSQL Database
- Python Backend
- Repository Layer
- Service Layer
- Seed Data Generator
- **CRUD** Features
- Enrollment Workflow
- Attendance Workflow
- Examination Workflow
- Payment Workflow
- Reporting Module
- Test Suite
- Query Optimization Notes
- Project Documentation

---

# Learning Outcomes

After completing this project, you should be able to:

- Design normalized relational databases.
- Model complex one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships.
- Use PostgreSQL features such as CTEs, window functions, **JSONB**, views, materialized views, and `**EXPLAIN** **ANALYZE**`.
- Build a layered Python backend that separates database access from business logic.
- Write production-style reporting queries.
- Diagnose and optimize query performance.
- Explain your design decisions and trade-offs in technical interviews.